# Hire and onboard a new contractor (3–5 weeks)

## Context

Identify a recurring delivery bottleneck, scope a contractor role, source 5–10 candidates, pick one, sign a contractor agreement, and run them through onboarding so they ship billable work in week 3.

## Outcome

By the end of this playbook, the operator has run the 6 stages below and produced the written decision artefact in the final stage.

Success criteria:

- All 6 stages have written outputs in the project record
- Each stage's decision gate was answered before advancing (yes / no in writing)
- Final stage produced the required written decision artifact
- Every methodology reference loaded cleanly via `faion get-content`

## Steps

### 1. Diagnose Bottleneck

Identify the recurring delivery bottleneck a contractor will solve.

Tasks:
- Map the last 3 projects' time logs to find repeated overflow tasks
- Quantify hours-per-month lost to the bottleneck
- Decide: contractor vs automation vs decline-the-work

Outputs:
- bottleneck analysis
- hours/month figure
- hire-or-not memo

Decision gate: Advance only if ≥40 hrs/month is consistently lost and contractor is the chosen lever.

### 2. Scope Role

Write a tight contractor role that the bench can deliver against.

Tasks:
- Draft a 1-page contractor job description with outputs not duties
- Set a fixed monthly engagement envelope and rate band
- Define the paid test task and its scoring rubric

Outputs:
- contractor JD
- rate band
- test-task brief + rubric

Decision gate: Advance when JD fits on one page AND test task is reproducible across candidates.

### 3. Source 5-10

Run a small structured sourcing batch.

Tasks:
- Post in 2 channels + ask 5 trusted contacts for referrals
- Screen for portfolio match and timezone fit before any interview
- Send the paid test task to top 3-5 candidates

Outputs:
- sourcing log
- screening notes
- paid-test results

Decision gate: Advance if ≥2 candidates cleared the test task with a score above the rubric bar.

### 4. Interview & Decide

Pick one, sign legally clean.

Tasks:
- Run a 30-min structured interview using the STAR framework
- Reference-check at least one past client
- Sign a contractor agreement matching jurisdiction

Outputs:
- interview notes
- reference summary
- signed contractor agreement

Decision gate: Advance only when contract is countersigned and start date is on calendar.

### 5. Onboard

First week sets the tone; ship billable work in week 3.

Tasks:
- Run the onboarding runbook: access, docs, comms norms, weekly cadence
- Pair on one real piece of work in week 1
- Assign the first billable deliverable for week 3

Outputs:
- onboarding checklist completed
- pairing notes
- week-3 deliverable

Decision gate: Advance when contractor ships the week-3 deliverable to a client without rework.

### 6. 30-day Review

Lock or unwind the engagement on evidence.

Tasks:
- Score the contractor against the JD outputs at day 30
- Run a frank 1:1 on what's working and what isn't
- Decide: continue / change scope / end engagement

Outputs:
- 30-day scorecard
- 1:1 notes
- continue/change/end decision

Decision gate: Required output: a written continue / change / end decision.

## Decision points

- Stage 1 (Diagnose Bottleneck): Advance only if ≥40 hrs/month is consistently lost and contractor is the chosen lever.
- Stage 2 (Scope Role): Advance when JD fits on one page AND test task is reproducible across candidates.
- Stage 3 (Source 5-10): Advance if ≥2 candidates cleared the test task with a score above the rubric bar.
- Stage 4 (Interview & Decide): Advance only when contract is countersigned and start date is on calendar.
- Stage 5 (Onboard): Advance when contractor ships the week-3 deliverable to a client without rework.
- Stage 6 (30-day Review): Required output: a written continue / change / end decision.

